event_investment_decisions.event_description:
In the upcoming MLB game, scheduled for September 17 at 7:40PM ET:
If the Los Angeles Angels win, the market will resolve to “Angels”.
If the Milwaukee Brewers win, the market will resolve to “Brewers”.
If the game is postponed, this market will remain open until the game has been completed.
If the game is canceled entirely, with no make-up game, this market will resolve 50-50.
To know when a postponed game will be played, please check the home team's schedule on MLB.com for the listed team and look for the game described as a makeup game.

decision.rationale: The September 17, 2025 Angels vs. Brewers game has already been played. Multiple reputable sources (ESPN, MLB.com, CBS Sports) report a final score of Brewers 9, Angels 2. Therefore the Brewers won outright. The market price for the Angels outcome is 0.0355, reflecting a ~96% implied probability that the Brewers win, which matches the observed result. There is no mispricing to exploit, so we place no bet.

The spread market asks whether the Brewers win by 2 or more runs. The final margin was 7 runs, so the correct outcome is "Yes" (Brewers cover). The market price for a Brewers win (i.e., Yes) is 0.85, implying a 85% chance, consistent with the known result. No mispricing; we do not bet.

The over/under market is set at 7.5 runs. The combined total was 11 runs, so the "Over" outcome is correct. The market price for Over is 0.82, implying an 82% chance, which aligns with the actual outcome. No exploitable discrepancy; we place no bet.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Los Angeles Angels vs. Milwaukee Brewers: O/U 7.5

decision.rationale: The NRFI market pays Yes if no runs are scored in the 1st inning. The game recap shows the Brewers hit a three‑run homer in the first inning, meaning runs were scored. The correct outcome is "No". The market price for Yes is 0.9955, nearly 100% probability that No will occur, correctly pricing the event. No mispricing to exploit; we bet nothing.

event_investment_decisions.event_description:
The FED interest rates are defined in this market by the upper bound of the target federal funds range. The decisions on the target federal fund range are made by the Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) meetings.

This market will resolve to the amount of basis points the upper bound of the target federal funds rate is changed by versus the level it was prior to the Federal Reserve's October 2025 meeting.

If the target federal funds rate is changed to a level not expressed in the displayed options, the change will be rounded up to the nearest 25 and will resolve to the relevant bracket. (e.g. if there's a cut/increase of 12.5 bps it will be considered to be 25 bps)

The resolution source for this market is the FOMC’s statement after its meeting scheduled for October 28 - 29, 2025 according to the official calendar: https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/fomccalendars.htm.

The level and change of the target federal funds rate is also published at the official website of the Federal Reserve at https://www.federalreserve.gov/monetarypolicy/openmarket.htm.

This market may resolve as soon as the FOMC’s statement for their October meeting with relevant data is issued. If no statement is released by the end date of the next scheduled meeting, this market will resolve to the "No change" bracket.

decision.rationale: The market currently prices a 78.5% probability that the Fed will cut the policy rate by 25 bps at the October 2025 meeting. Recent developments – a 25 bps cut at the September 16‑17 meeting and multiple statements from Fed officials indicating a willingness to ease further – suggest the Fed is on an easing path, but the September cut already delivered the first quarter‑point reduction of the cycle. Historically, after an initial cut, the Fed often pauses before delivering a second identical cut, especially when inflation is still above target. Moreover, the median dot‑plot now projects only two more cuts for the remainder of 2025, implying the October meeting may be a pause point. Hence I estimate the true probability of a 25 bps cut at about 70 % – lower than the market’s implied 78.5 %. I therefore short this outcome.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Fed decreases interest rates by 25 bps after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: The market prices a 14.5% chance of "no change" after the October meeting. Given the recent 25 bps reduction in September and the Fed’s expressed desire to keep inflation moving toward 2% while maintaining financial stability, a modest pause is plausible. The Fed’s own projections (dot‑plot) still allow for a pause in the October meeting before resuming cuts later in the year. Combining those factors, I assess a 20% probability of no change – higher than the market’s implied 14.5% – indicating underpricing. I therefore go long on the "no change" outcome.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: No change in Fed interest rates after October 2025 meeting?

decision.rationale: A 50 bps (or larger) cut is priced at 7.35% by the market. Recent statements and the modest 25 bps cut just taken suggest the Fed is unlikely to deliver a deep cut this month; the Fed’s minutes from September show only a few participants supporting a larger move, and the median projection still shows only two more cuts of 25 bps each for the rest of 2025. Thus the true probability of a 50 bps cut is probably closer to 5%, slightly lower than the market’s price. I take a small short position.

market_investment_decisions.market_question: Fed decreases interest rates by 50+ bps after October 2025 meeting?
